i. Cognitive restructuring: Therapists guide clients to identify and challenge irrational or unhelpful thoughts and replace them with more adaptive and realistic beliefs.
ii. Behavioral activation: Clients are encouraged to engage in activities that align with their values and personal goals, promoting a sense of mastery and accomplishment.
iii. Exposure therapy: Clients confront feared situations, thoughts, or emotions under the guidance of the therapist, gradually reducing anxiety and avoidance behaviors.
iv. Problem-solving therapy: Therapists teach clients a structured approach to address challenges and make decisions, fostering self-efficacy and resilience.
v. Psychoeducation: Clients learn about their mental health condition, its symptoms, and the rationale behind CBT interventions, empowering them to manage their own recovery.